Five cities share trade, diplomacy, and unresolved historical debt across a continent organized around desert oasis routes, forest corridors, and coastal sea lanes.
Midgaard anchors law and registration at the continent's inland crossroads; its registries and charter systems are the reference standard for legitimacy disputes.
Kiess secures northern frontier logistics along the Roc Road built on Evermeet's ruins; its anti-secrecy doctrine and three-power governance are the most formally principled in the network.
Kowloon stabilizes crisis corridors with Neon Covenant wall protocol and ration governance; it moves goods and counts them with institutional discipline.
Rakuen is the disaster-recovery municipality, absorbing costs other cities classify away; it has been petitioned three times for Midgaard annexation and refused three times.
Mafdet is the maritime conversion point at the Saltglass Reach's terminus where inland desert law meets sea commerce and both must adapt.
Together they form a legitimacy corridor: origin claim, overland custody, dispute adjudication, hazard screening, ocean transfer. Each function requires a different city.
The corridor is not an alliance. It is a co-dependency none of the five fully chose and none can easily exit without the others accumulating strain.
Historical debts include: the Evermeet collapse that made Kiess necessary, the Plague Mandate that still haunts Shadowmere's legal status, the Ninth Meridian catastrophe's unresolved territorial consequences.
Five major non-human peoples — Khenari, Khephari, Ashborn, Umbral, Rivennid — and five secondary peoples — Deltari, Ushabti, Serathi, Kethari — participate in city governance, trade, and institutional memory to varying degrees.
The Keepers of Measure were the earliest civilization to leave functional records; most surviving institutional forms derive from their calibration-based governance.
The Solar Court, Moon Sovereign, and Jackal Synod are the major post-Keeper religious-political traditions whose rivalry shaped the catastrophes that produced the current five-city configuration.

