Mafdet understands the five-city realm as a conversion system: value produced inland must reach the sea, and the sea's standards must be satisfied at the point of conversion.
The city's position at the Saltglass Reach's terminus means it processes every inland claim through the test of maritime legitimacy.
Documents that satisfy Midgaard's charter requirements may not satisfy Mafdet's Quarantine Ledger standards. Documents that satisfy the Claw Mark Registry may not satisfy Kowloon's Black Ledger.
Mafdet's Shoreward Conversion is not merely a historical practice: it is a daily institutional negotiation between two legal systems that have never fully reconciled.
From Mafdet's perspective, the realm works when every city's standards are legible to every other city's systems. It fails when cities speak only to their own registries.
The Strandline Compact's harbor-first principle means Mafdet's political decisions are always tested against throughput: does this decision help goods move? If not, revise.
Mafdet's relationships: most commercially aligned with Kowloon on throughput governance; most institutionally aligned with Midgaard on authentication standards; most geographically isolated from Kiess but dependent on Kiess route law for inland caravan certification.
The Shrine of the First Claw's oath tradition positions Mafdet as the realm's trust-enforcement terminus: the place where inland promises meet the sea's accountability.
Mafdet's assessment of the realm: it is a chain. The chain is only as strong as its weakest conversion point. Mafdet is the last conversion point.
